---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
import { BAND_COLORS, companyBySlug, data, fmtPts, scoringReference } from '../lib/data';
import { BAND_THRESHOLDS, computeScore } from '../lib/scoring';
import { BandChip, GradientBar, SectionHeading } from '../components/ui.tsx';

const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL;

const EXAMPLES = [
  {
    slug: 'apple',
    lesson:
      'Sustained structural commitment — benefits, policy, a long consistent record — pushes far past the cosmetic cap and held publicly through the 2025 backlash. Structure is what the formula rewards most.',
  },
  {
    slug: 'verizon',
    lesson:
      'Years of visible support — branding, sponsorships, a funded ERG — erased by a written 2025 reversal under regulatory pressure. Support that evaporates when it carries a cost is scored as what the evaporation reveals.',
  },
  {
    slug: 'salesforce',
    lesson:
      'A reversal hurts even an ally: real negative points for sanding the public edges off its commitments. But deep structural investment absorbs the blow — the score drops without collapsing.',
  },
  {
    slug: 'tesla',
    lesson:
      'Nothing positive on the record and documented negative actions: the baseline offers no shelter. With no support to lose, negative points fall straight through to the bottom band.',
  },
  {
    slug: 'southern-company',
    lesson:
      'Real internal substance — policy and benefits — but no Commercial or Civic public engagement at all. The engagement factor discounts that quiet substance by 15%, the symmetric counterpart to the pride-washing penalty: it edges below a perfect score where an otherwise-identical company that also showed up publicly would not.',
  },
];

const examples = EXAMPLES.map((e) => {
  const ex = companyBySlug.get(e.slug);
  return ex ? { ...e, ex, b: computeScore(ex.actions) } : null;
}).filter((x): x is NonNullable<typeof x> => x !== null);

const formula = `score = clamp( 0, 100,
         50                                                // neutral baseline
       + min(20, cosmetic + commercial)                    // capped "signaling"
       + diminish(civic + financial + structural) × engage // substantive positives
       + diminish(negatives) )                              // negatives`;
---

<Layout
  title="Methodology — The Corporate Pride Index"
  description="Scoring Methodology v2.1: the +20 signaling cap, diminishing returns, the engagement factor, reversal asymmetry, the six bands, worked examples, and the full point-value reference."
  path="methodology"
>
  <div class="doc">
    <div class="page">
      <span class="kick">Built for public scrutiny</span>
      <h1>Methodology</h1>
      <p class="intro">This index exists to answer one question: when a company puts a rainbow on its
        logo, is there anything underneath? You should never have to trust our judgment — every number
        on this site is recomputed from sourced, public actions each time the site is built, and every
        action carries its citation.</p>
    </div>

    <section class="section">
      <div class="prose">
        <div class="d-k">The framework · version 2.1</div>
        <h2>How a score is built</h2>
        <p>Every company starts at <strong>50</strong> — neutral. Nothing is owed; nothing is presumed.
          From there, documented actions move the score across five positive tiers and a severity-ranked
          set of negatives. Positive and negative points are summed separately and meet at the baseline:</p>
      </div>
      <div class="formula">{formula}</div>
      <div class="prose">
        <p><strong>The +20 signaling cap.</strong> Rainbow logos, Pride posts, and merchandise collections
          (the Cosmetic and Commercial tiers) are real but cheap. Their combined value is capped at 20
          points — a company cannot post its way into being an ally. To clear the Neutral band it must
          spend, show up, or change policy. This cap is applied before diminishing returns.</p>
        <p><strong>Reversal asymmetry.</strong> Negatives are individually heavier than their positive
          counterparts (lobbying against LGBTQ+ legislation costs −40; an explicit pro-LGBTQ+ DEI policy
          earns +20), and the single largest negative always lands at full weight — so a decisive reversal
          still pushes a company below the baseline. Adopting a policy in calm weather is weak evidence of
          commitment; abandoning one under pressure is strong evidence of its absence. A company that built
          a record and then reversed scores worse than one that never committed at all.</p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section">
      <div class="prose">
        <div class="d-k">The core of v2</div>
        <h2>Diminishing returns</h2>
        <p>Substantive positives (Civic, Financial, Structural) and negatives are each scored with
          <strong>diminishing returns</strong>: within each pool the actions are sorted largest-first, and
          every successive action is multiplied by a decreasing weight. The single most significant action
          on each side carries full weight; additional similar actions count for progressively less.</p>
        <div class="formula">position   1st    2nd    3rd    4th    5th    6th    7th   8th+
weight    1.00   0.70   0.50   0.35   0.25   0.15   0.10   0.05</div>
        <p>v1 capped cheap positive signaling but summed negatives without limit, which compressed both
          ends of the scale: soft, partial reversers floored at 0 alongside the worst actors, while the
          most committed companies piled past 100 and flattened to an identical top score. Applying the
          same diminishing logic to both tails keeps the 0–100 scale resolving at both extremes — doing
          many good (or bad) things still moves the score, but neither runs away to the clamp on volume
          alone.</p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section">
      <div class="prose">
        <div class="d-k">New in v2.1</div>
        <h2>The engagement factor</h2>
        <p>The model penalizes <em>visible signaling without substance</em> — the pride-washing action.
          The engagement factor is its mirror image: <em>substance without visibility</em>. A company's
          diminished substantive subtotal is multiplied by <strong>0.85</strong> when it has no
          public-facing engagement at all — no Commercial action (merch, collaborations) and no Civic
          action (parades, marching, funded ERGs, community events). Only internal substance, never shown.</p>
        <p>A bare Cosmetic gesture — a rainbow logo, a generic post, a flag — is too cheap to count as
          engagement, so it does not lift the factor. The discount lands at roughly the same magnitude as
          the pride-washing penalty, so the two cases are treated symmetrically: a company that quietly
          holds policy and benefits scores just below an otherwise-identical company that also shows up
          publicly. It does not erase a strong record — substantive support still dominates the score — it
          simply stops "do it quietly" from tying "do it and stand behind it."</p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section">
      <div class="prose"><div class="d-k">Reading the number</div><h2>The six bands</h2></div>
      <div style="margin:18px 0 14px"><GradientBar showLabels /></div>
      <div class="bandcard">
        {
          BAND_THRESHOLDS.map((b) => (
            <div class="bandrow">
              <BandChip band={b.band} />
              <span style={{ fontFamily: 'var(--mono)', color: BAND_COLORS[b.band] }}>{b.min}–{b.max}</span>
            </div>
          ))
        }
      </div>
      <p class="prose" style="margin-top:14px">The rainbow appears on this site as the 0–100 score
        gradient — it is not decoration, it is the measurement scale itself.</p>
    </section>

    <section class="section">
      <div class="prose">
        <div class="d-k">The framework in practice</div>
        <h2>Worked examples</h2>
        <p>Five companies, five patterns the formula is built to distinguish. Each breakdown below is
          computed live from the company's logged actions — the same arithmetic that produces every
          score on this site.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="worked">
        {
          examples.map(({ slug, lesson, ex, b }) => (
            <div class="wcard">
              <div class="wh">
                <a class="wn" href={`${base}company/${slug}`}>{ex.name}</a>
                <span style="display:flex;align-items:center;gap:8px">
                  <span style={{ fontFamily: 'var(--serif)', fontSize: '26px', color: BAND_COLORS[b.band] }}>{b.score}</span>
                  <BandChip band={b.band} />
                </span>
              </div>
              <table class="brk">
                <tbody>
                  <tr><td>Baseline</td><td class="v">50</td></tr>
                  <tr>
                    <td>Cosmetic + Commercial (cap 20){b.cosmeticCommercialRaw > b.cosmeticCommercialCapped ? ` · raw +${b.cosmeticCommercialRaw}` : ''}</td>
                    <td class="v pos">+{b.cosmeticCommercialCapped}</td>
                  </tr>
                  <tr><td>Substantive — diminished{b.substantiveRaw > b.substantiveDiminished ? ` · raw +${b.substantiveRaw}` : ''}{b.engagementFactor < 1 ? ` · ×${b.engagementFactor} engagement` : ''}</td><td class="v pos">+{Math.round((b.positiveCapped - b.cosmeticCommercialCapped) * 10) / 10}</td></tr>
                  <tr><td>Negatives — diminished{b.negativeRaw < b.negative ? ` · raw ${b.negativeRaw}` : ''}</td><td class="v neg">{b.negative}</td></tr>
                  <tr class="tot"><td>Score</td><td class="v" style={{ color: BAND_COLORS[b.band] }}>{b.score}</td></tr>
                </tbody>
              </table>
              <p class="lesson">{lesson}</p>
            </div>
          ))
        }
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section">
      <div class="prose"><div class="d-k">The point values</div><h2>Full scoring reference</h2></div>
      <div class="refwrap" style="margin-top:14px">
        <table>
          <thead><tr>
            <th>Action ID</th><th>Tier</th><th class="r">Points</th><th>Description</th>
          </tr></thead>
          <tbody>
            {
              scoringReference.map((r) => (
                <tr style="cursor:default">
                  <td class="tkr">{r.actionId}</td>
                  <td class="sec">{r.tier}</td>
                  <td class="r mono" style={{ color: r.points > 0 ? 'var(--good)' : 'var(--bad)' }}>{fmtPts(r.points)}</td>
                  <td>{r.description}</td>
                </tr>
              ))
            }
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section">
      <div class="prose">
        <div class="d-k">Why you can check us</div>
        <h2>Sourcing standards</h2>
        <p>Every action in the index — all {data.validation.actionsChecked} of them — is a discrete, dated,
          publicly documented event with a source URL attached: news reporting, company press releases and
          filings, archived web pages, or the HRC Corporate Equality Index. Where companies deleted the
          evidence (Pride posts, DEI pages), we cite archives and reporting on the deletion — the deletion
          itself is part of the record.</p>
        <p>Each company page also carries a one-line verdict, the drivers in both directions, and the
          decisive factor, written by the analyst — but the prose never moves the number. Only logged
          actions do.</p>
        <p>At build time the site recomputes every score from raw actions with the v2 formula above and
          asserts it matches the workbook's stored aggregates and yearly-series anchors, and verifies every
          action's point value against the fixed scoring reference. This build:{' '}
          <strong style={{ color: data.validation.passed ? 'var(--good)' : 'var(--bad)' }}>
            {data.validation.passed ? `all ${data.validation.companiesChecked} companies validated ✓` : 'VALIDATION FAILED'}
          </strong>.</p>
        <p style="color:var(--txt-mut)">Disagree with a point value or think we missed an action? Good —
          that's the point of publishing the rubric. Every input is inspectable, so the argument can be
          about evidence, not vibes.</p>
      </div>
    </section>
  </div>
</Layout>
